func2 will never return ZeroDivisionError as this error was never raised in the try block. In the try block, you are just returning the output of func1 which will never throw an error.

You can try:

    def func1(a, b):
        try:
            return a/b
        except ZeroDivisionError as e:
            print(&quot;0&quot;)


    def func2(func):
        return func

If you must put the check in `func2` you will need to make sure that the computation is happening inside `func2`. In your case, the call is `func2(func1(1,0))`. So what is happening under the hood is, when `func2` calls `func1(1,0)`, it is not computing the `func1` inside it, instead it is taking the value of `func(1,0)`, i.e. it is asking `func1` to do its calculation in its own scope, and return only the value. `func1` encounters a `ZeroDivisionError` without entering the `Try` block of `func2`. Your actual function call becomes `func2(return_val_of_func1(1,0))`. So you are essentially checking whether the value of `func1` throws any `ZeroDivisionError`, which is not possible. So instead, what you can do is:
```
def func1(a, b):
    return a/b

def func2(func1,a,b):
    try:
        return func1(a,b)
    except ZeroDivisionError as e:
        print(&quot;0&quot;)

func2(func1,1,0)
```

